        <h2 id="examples">Real Knowledge Graph optimization examples</h2>
        <p>Two patterns show what KGO looks like in practice.</p>

        <h3>Example 1: B2B SaaS brand starting from zero</h3>
        <p>A project management tool with no knowledge panel runs a 6-month KGO campaign:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Adds Organization JSON-LD to homepage with <code>sameAs</code> pointing to LinkedIn, Crunchbase, G2</li>
          <li>Creates a Wikidata entry with correct entity type, founding date, CEO, and product category</li>
          <li>Earns 3 industry publication mentions (TechCrunch, Product Hunt, G2) in the same quarter</li>
          <li>Submits to 60 business directories with identical name/URL/description</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Result: Knowledge panel appears for branded searches within 5 months. AI Overviews for "best project management software for teams" start citing the brand within 7 months.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: Local dental practice</h3>
        <p>A 3-location dental group implements LocalBusiness schema with geo coordinates on each location page, verifies and fully completes GBP for all 3 locations, builds 55 consistent citations, and earns 12 local press mentions. Within 4 months, knowledge panels appear for each location's branded search, and the practice appears in the Local Pack for "dentist near me" queries in all 3 service areas.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Knowledge Graph optimization vs. technical SEO — how they interact</h2>
        <p>KGO and traditional technical SEO address different parts of Google's understanding system.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Knowledge Graph optimization</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Targets Google's entity database</li>
              <li>Affects branded search, panels, AI Overviews</li>
              <li>Builds long-term topical authority</li>
              <li>Works via schema, citations, Wikidata, mentions</li>
              <li>Results compound over months</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Technical SEO</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Targets Google's crawl and index layer</li>
              <li>Affects page ranking in organic results</li>
              <li>Fixes blocking issues (speed, redirects, errors)</li>
              <li>Works via crawlability, structured markup, Core Web Vitals</li>
              <li>Results often visible within days to weeks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 Knowledge Graph optimization best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with entity name consistency.</strong> Pick one canonical form of your brand name and enforce it everywhere: website, GBP, LinkedIn, Crunchbase, directories, and schema markup. Inconsistencies create entity confusion and delay Knowledge Graph recognition.</li>
          <li><strong>Implement Organization JSON-LD on your homepage.</strong> Include: <code>@type</code>, <code>name</code>, <code>url</code>, <code>logo</code>, <code>foundingDate</code>, <code>description</code>, <code>sameAs</code> array, and <code>contactPoint</code>.</li>
          <li><strong>Create a Wikidata entry.</strong> Wikidata is directly consumed by Google's Knowledge Graph. A complete entry with entity type, key attributes, and sameAs links to your website and Wikipedia accelerates recognition significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Build citation coverage to 50+ directories.</strong> Yelp, Bing Places, Apple Maps, BBB, Foursquare, Yellow Pages, Angi, and industry-specific directories. All must show identical name, address, phone, and website URL.</li>
          <li><strong>Add sameAs links to every authoritative profile.</strong> Your Organization schema's <code>sameAs</code> array should include: Wikipedia, Wikidata, LinkedIn, Twitter/X, Crunchbase, G2 or Capterra (for SaaS), Facebook, and any industry-specific profile.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn mentions on Google-trusted sources.</strong> Crunchbase, Bloomberg, Reuters, industry trade publications, and government databases all carry high entity signal weight. One mention from TechCrunch can do what 50 directory listings cannot.</li>
          <li><strong>Claim and verify your Google Business Profile.</strong> GBP verification is Google's own confirmation of your entity's existence and location. It feeds the Knowledge Graph directly and is the fastest KGO win for local businesses.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor entity health monthly.</strong> Search your brand name monthly. Check whether your knowledge panel is accurate, whether your description has changed, and whether any incorrect facts appear. Use the "Claim this knowledge panel" option to gain suggestion rights.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating KGO as a one-time task</div>
          <p>Knowledge Graph data decays. Wikipedia pages get edited, citations become inconsistent, Wikidata entries get outdated. Brands that optimize once and walk away often find their knowledge panels showing incorrect information 12 months later. Monthly monitoring and quarterly citation audits are the maintenance minimum.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Knowledge Graph optimization mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Missing sameAs links.</strong> Organization schema without sameAs is the single most common KGO gap. Google can't confirm your site and your Wikipedia page are the same entity without this link.</li>
          <li><strong>Wikidata entry with missing properties.</strong> A Wikidata entry with only a name and description contributes little. Add entity type (P31), official website (P856), founding date (P571), CEO (P169), and social profiles.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent NAP across citations.</strong> "Acme Corp" in GBP, "Acme Corporation" in Yelp, and "Acme" in Yellow Pages are three separate entities to Google's entity matcher.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting to claim the knowledge panel.</strong> Once your panel appears, claiming it via Google Search Console gives you the ability to suggest edits to description, images, and links — directly influencing what Google shows for your branded searches.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping Wikidata for Wikipedia.</strong> Wikidata is easier to create and contributes directly to the Knowledge Graph. Many brands skip it because it lacks Wikipedia's prestige, but it's often more impactful in the short term.</li>
        </ul>

